# Command line-reorder

## What does this command do:

Allow you to reorder lines by drag and drop using a GUI

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: sudo dnf install python3-pyside6 && git clone https://github.com/kevinpinscoe/line-reorder-gui /tmp/lrg && cp /tmp/lrg/line_reorder.py /tmp/lrg/line-reorder ~/bin/ && chmod +x ~/bin/line-reorder
For Raspberry Pi install using: pip install --user PySide6 && git clone https://github.com/kevinpinscoe/line-reorder-gui /tmp/lrg && cp /tmp/lrg/line_reorder.py /tmp/lrg/line-reorder ~/bin/ && chmod +x ~/bin/line-reorder
For Mac install using: pip install --user PySide6 && git clone https://github.com/kevinpinscoe/line-reorder-gui /tmp/lrg && cp /tmp/lrg/line_reorder.py /tmp/lrg/line-reorder ~/bin/ && chmod +x ~/bin/line-reorder

## Command path

For Fedora run: ~/bin/line-reorder
For Raspberry Pi run: ~/bin/line-reorder
For Mac run: ~/bin/line-reorder

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://github.com/kevinpinscoe/line-reorder-gui

## Command options

line-reorder /full/path/to/file.txt   # open file in GUI for drag-and-drop line reordering
